    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="593"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d593">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/1553</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-29">December 29,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary</hi>: The attached report<note n="89"
                        xml:id="d593fn89">Not printed.</note> of the F. B. I.<note n="90"
                        xml:id="d593fn90">Federal Bureau of Investigation.</note> relates to the
                    activities of the Japanese Consulate in Hawaii and its complicity in the bombing
                    of Pearl Harbor.</p>
                <p>It will be noted that the F. B. I. wished to prosecute a number of the Japanese
                    agents, first raising the question in the Summer of 1941. The Department of
                    Justice consulted the State Department in July, 1941, and were advised that the
                    State Department assented to the prosecution.</p>
                <p>Prosecution of these agents never was carried out, owing to the objection of the
                    War Department.</p>
                <p>The record is important because it makes clear the fact that the position of the
                    Department was at all times plain.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>A[<hi rend="smallcaps">dolf</hi>] A. B[<hi rend="smallcaps">erle</hi>],
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jr</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
